<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-02T01:25:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-02T01:25:00-05:00" n="267" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d267">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/4236: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>)
                                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Addis
                                            Ababa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-02T09:00:00+02:35">May 2, 1936—9
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>261. Apparently Government left during the night. Empress with
                                daughters and Prince Makonnen by train for Djibouti understand en
                                route to Jerusalem. Emperor’s destination unknown. Spencer<note n="18" xml:id="d267fn18">John H. Spencer, an American citizen
                                    who was Adviser to the Ethiopian Ministry of Foreign
                                    Affairs.</note> and Lambies<note n="19" xml:id="d267fn19">Dr.
                                    and Mrs. T. A. Lambie. Dr. Lambie was Executive Secretary of the
                                    Ethiopian Bed Cross.</note> did not accompany the
                                Government.</p>
                            <p>As soon as news of the departure of Government became known looting
                                began in town which is continuing. There is a great deal of firing
                                but mostly in the air. I shall await developments in the Legation
                                for the present.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>